The paper introduces a novel architecture for deep reinforcement learning (RL) for web navigation tasks, which involves understanding and interacting with structured language (HTML). This suggests that the paper could belong to several arXiv CS sub-categories, including cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.LG (Machine Learning), which are both highly relevant to RL. Additionally, the paper's use of graph neural networks to represent the tree-structured HTML suggests that it could also belong to cs.CL (Computation and Language) or cs.CV (Computer Vision), which both involve understanding and processing structured data. Finally, the paper's focus on improving the efficiency of RL training for web navigation tasks suggests that it could also belong to cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction), which involves designing and evaluating interactive systems.
